# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: buckingham-potential
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] The ability to run these calculations has enabled theoretical chemists to solve a range of problems and their importance is highlighted by the awarding of the 1998 Nobel prize to John Pople and Walter Kohn.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] The term *ab initio* was first used in quantum chemistry by Robert Parr and coworkers, including David Craig in a semiempirical study on the excited states of benzene.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] One needs to consider the computational cost of *ab initio* methods when determining whether they are appropriate for the problem at hand.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] When compared to much less accurate approaches, such as molecular mechanics, *ab initio* methods often take larger amounts of computer time, memory, and disk space, though, with modern advances in computer science and technology such considerations are becoming less of an issue.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] However, in practice it can scale closer to *N*3 as the program can identify zero and extremely small integrals and neglect them.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Correlated calculations scale less favorably, though their accuracy is usually greater, which is the trade off one needs to consider.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] One popular method is Møller–Plesset perturbation theory (MP).
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] To second order (MP2), MP scales as *N*4.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] To fourth order (MP4) MP scales as *N*7.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Another method, coupled cluster with singles and doubles (CCSD), scales as *N*6 and extensions, CCSD(T) and CR-CC(2,3), scale as *N*6 with one noniterative step which scales as *N*7.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Hybrid Density functional theory (DFT) methods using functionals which include Hartree–Fock exchange scale in a similar manner to Hartree–Fock but with a larger proportionality term and are thus more expensive than an equivalent Hartree–Fock calculation.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Local DFT methods that do not include Hartree–Fock exchange can scale better than Hartree–Fock.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] The problem of computational expense can be alleviated through simplification schemes.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] In the *density fitting* scheme, the four-index integrals used to describe the interaction between electron pairs are reduced to simpler two- or three-index integrals, by treating the charge densities they contain in a simplified way.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] This reduces the scaling with respect to basis set size.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Methods employing this scheme are denoted by the prefix "df-", for example the density fitting MP2 is df-MP2 (many authors use lower-case to prevent confusion with DFT).
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] This sharply reduces the scaling with molecular size, a major problem in the treatment of biologically-sized molecules.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Methods employing this scheme are denoted by the prefix "L", e.g.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Both schemes can be employed together, as in the df-LMP2 and df-LCCSD(T0) methods.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] In fact, df-LMP2 calculations are faster than df-Hartree–Fock calculations and thus are feasible in nearly all situations in which also DFT is.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] The simplest type of *ab initio* electronic structure calculation is the Hartree–Fock (HF) scheme, in which the instantaneous Coulombic electron-electron repulsion is not specifically taken into account.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Only its average effect (mean field) is included in the calculation.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] This is a variational procedure; therefore, the obtained approximate energies, expressed in terms of the system's wave function, are always equal to or greater than the exact energy, and tend to a limiting value called the Hartree–Fock limit as the size of the basis is increased.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Many types of calculations begin with a Hartree–Fock calculation and subsequently correct for electron-electron repulsion, referred to also as electronic correlation.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Møller–Plesset perturbation theory (MP*n*) and coupled cluster theory (CC) are examples of these post-Hartree–Fock methods.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] In some cases, particularly for bond breaking processes, the Hartree–Fock method is inadequate and this single-determinant reference function is not a good basis for post-Hartree–Fock methods.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] It is then necessary to start with a wave function that includes more than one determinant such as multi-configurational self-consistent field (MCSCF) and methods have been developed that use these multi-determinant references for improvements.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] However, if one uses coupled cluster methods such as CCSDT, CCSDt, CR-CC(2,3), or CC(t;3) then single-bond breaking using the single determinant HF reference is feasible.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] For an accurate description of double bond breaking, methods such as CCSDTQ, CCSDTq, CCSDtq, CR-CC(2,4), or CC(tq;3,4) also make use of the single determinant HF reference, and do not require one to use multi-reference methods.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] A series of *ab initio* studies of Si2H2 is an example of how *ab initio* computational chemistry can predict new structures that are subsequently confirmed by experiment.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] They go back over 20 years, and most of the main conclusions were reached by 1995.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] The methods used were mostly post-Hartree–Fock, particularly configuration interaction (CI) and coupled cluster (CC).
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Initially the question was whether disilyne, Si2H2 had the same structure as ethyne (acetylene), C2H2.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Interest then moved to look at whether structures equivalent to vinylidene (Si=SiH2) existed.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] This structure is predicted to be a local minimum, i.e. an isomer of Si2H2, lying higher in energy than the ground state but below the energy of the trans-bent isomer.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Then a new isomer with an unusual structure was predicted by Brenda Colegrove in Henry F.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] It requires post-Hartree–Fock methods to obtain a local minimum for this structure.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] It does not exist on the Hartree–Fock energy hypersurface.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] The new isomer is a planar structure with one bridging hydrogen atom and one terminal hydrogen atom, cis to the bridging atom.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Its energy is above the ground state but below that of the other isomers.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Similar results were later obtained for Ge2H2.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Al2H2 and Ga2H2 have exactly the same isomers, in spite of having two electrons less than the Group 14 molecules.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] The only difference is that the four-membered ring ground state is planar and not bent.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] The cis-mono-bridged and vinylidene-like isomers are present.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Experimental work on these molecules is not easy, but matrix isolation spectroscopy of the products of the reaction of hydrogen atoms and silicon and aluminium surfaces has found the ground state ring structures and the cis-mono-bridged structures for Si2H2 and Al2H2.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Theoretical predictions of the vibrational frequencies were crucial in understanding the experimental observations of the spectra of a mixture of compounds.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] This may appear to be an obscure area of chemistry, but the differences between carbon and silicon chemistry is always a lively question, as are the differences between group 13 and group 14 (mainly the B and C differences).
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] The silicon and germanium compounds were the subject of a Journal of Chemical Education article.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Valence bond (VB) methods are generally *ab initio* although some semi-empirical versions have been proposed.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] A method that avoids making the variational overestimation of HF in the first place is Quantum Monte Carlo (QMC), in its variational, diffusion, and Green's function forms.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] These methods work with an explicitly correlated wave function and evaluate integrals numerically using a Monte Carlo integration.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Such calculations can be very time-consuming.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] The accuracy of QMC depends strongly on the initial guess of many-body wave-functions and the form of the many-body wave-function.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] One simple choice is Slater-Jastrow wave-function in which the local correlations are treated with the Jastrow factor.
[src:buckingham-potential/ab-initio-quantum-chemistry-methods] Sign Learning Kink-based (SiLK) Quantum Monte Carlo (website): The Sign Learning Kink (SiLK) based Quantum Monte Carlo (QMC) method is based on Feynman's path integral formulation of quantum mechanics, and can reduce the minus sign problem when calculating energies in atomic and molecular systems.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Nearly all argon in Earth's atmosphere is radiogenic argon-40, derived from the decay of potassium-40 in Earth's crust.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] In the universe, argon-36 is by far the most common argon isotope, as it is the most easily produced by stellar nucleosynthesis in supernovas.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The name "argon" is derived from the Ancient Greek word ἀργόν, neuter singular form of ἀργός meaning 'lazy' or 'inactive', as a reference to the fact that the element undergoes almost no chemical reactions.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The complete octet (eight electrons) in the outer atomic shell makes argon stable and resistant to bonding with other elements.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Its triple point temperature of 83.8058 K is a defining fixed point in the International Temperature Scale of 1990.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is extracted industrially by the fractional distillation of liquid air.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] It is mostly used as an inert shielding gas in welding and other high-temperature industrial processes where ordinarily unreactive substances become reactive; for example, an argon atmosphere is used in graphite electric furnaces to prevent the graphite from burning.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] It is also used in incandescent and fluorescent lighting, and other gas-discharge tubes.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] It makes a distinctive blue-green gas laser.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] It is also used in fluorescent glow starters.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon has approximately the same solubility in water as oxygen and is 2.5 times more soluble in water than nitrogen.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is colorless, odorless, nonflammable and nontoxic as a solid, liquid or gas.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is chemically inert under most conditions and forms no confirmed stable compounds at room temperature.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Although argon is a noble gas, it can form some compounds under various extreme conditions.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon fluorohydride (HArF), a compound of argon with fluorine and hydrogen that is stable below 17 K (−256.1 °C; −429.1 °F), has been demonstrated.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Although the neutral ground-state chemical compounds of argon are presently limited to HArF, argon can form clathrates with water when atoms of argon are trapped in a lattice of water molecules.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Ions, such as ArH+ , and excited-state complexes, such as ArF, have been demonstrated.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Theoretical calculation predicts several more argon compounds that should be stable but have not yet been synthesized.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon was first isolated from air in 1894 by Lord Rayleigh and Sir William Ramsay at University College London by removing oxygen, carbon dioxide, water, and nitrogen from a sample of clean air.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] They first accomplished this by replicating an experiment of Henry Cavendish's.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The arc was powered by a battery of five Grove cells and a Ruhmkorff coil of medium size.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The alkali absorbed the oxides of nitrogen produced by the arc and also carbon dioxide.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] They operated the arc until no more reduction of volume of the gas could be seen for at least an hour or two and the spectral lines of nitrogen disappeared when the gas was examined.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The remaining oxygen was reacted with alkaline pyrogallate to leave behind an apparently non-reactive gas which they called argon.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Before isolating the gas, they had determined that nitrogen produced from chemical compounds was 0.5% lighter than nitrogen from the atmosphere.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The difference was slight, but it was important enough to attract their attention for many months.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] They concluded that there was another gas in the air mixed in with the nitrogen.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon was also encountered in 1882 through independent research of H.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Each observed new lines in the emission spectrum of air that did not match known elements.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Prior to 1957, the symbol for argon was "A".
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] This was changed to Ar after the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry published the work *Nomenclature of Inorganic Chemistry* in 1957.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon constitutes 0.934% by volume and 1.288% by mass of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Air is the primary industrial source of purified argon products.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is isolated from air by fractionation, most commonly by cryogenic fractional distillation, a process that also produces purified nitrogen, oxygen, neon, krypton and xenon.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Earth's crust and seawater contain 1.2 ppm and 0.45 ppm of argon, respectively.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Naturally occurring 40 K, with a half-life of 1.25×109 years, decays to stable 40 Ar (11.2%) by electron capture or positron emission, and also to stable 40 Ca (88.8%) by beta decay.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] These properties and ratios are used to determine the age of rocks by K–Ar dating.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] In Earth's atmosphere, 39 Ar is made by cosmic ray activity, primarily by neutron capture of 40 Ar followed by two-neutron emission.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] In the subsurface environment, it is also produced through neutron capture by 39 K, followed by proton emission.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] 37 Ar is created from the neutron capture by 40 Ca followed by an alpha particle emission as a result of subsurface nuclear explosions.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Between locations in the Solar System, the isotopic composition of argon varies greatly.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Where the major source of argon is the decay of 40 K in rocks, 40 Ar will be the dominant isotope, as it is on Earth.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon produced directly by stellar nucleosynthesis is dominated by the alpha-process nuclide 36 Ar.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Correspondingly, solar argon contains 84.6% 36 Ar (according to solar wind measurements), and the ratio of the three isotopes 36Ar : 38Ar : 40Ar in the atmospheres of the outer planets is 8400 : 1600 : 1.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] This contrasts with the low abundance of primordial 36 Ar in Earth's atmosphere, which is only 31.5 ppmv (= 9340 ppmv × 0.337%), comparable with that of neon (18.18 ppmv) on Earth and with interplanetary gasses, measured by probes.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The atmospheres of Mars, Mercury and Titan (the largest moon of Saturn) contain argon, predominantly as 40 Ar.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The predominance of radiogenic 40 Ar is the reason the standard atomic weight of terrestrial argon is greater than that of the next element, potassium, a fact that was puzzling when argon was discovered.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Mendeleev positioned the elements on his periodic table in order of atomic weight, but the inertness of argon suggested a placement *before* the reactive alkali metal.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Henry Moseley later solved this problem by showing that the periodic table is actually arranged in order of atomic number (see History of the periodic table).
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon's complete octet of electrons indicates full s and p subshells.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] This full valence shell makes argon very stable and extremely resistant to bonding with other elements.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Before 1962, argon and the other noble gases were considered to be chemically inert and unable to form compounds; however, compounds of the heavier noble gases have since been synthesized.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The first argon compound with tungsten pentacarbonyl, W(CO)5Ar, was isolated in 1975.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] However, it was not widely recognised at that time.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] In August 2000, another argon compound, argon fluorohydride (HArF), was formed by researchers at the University of Helsinki, by shining ultraviolet light onto frozen argon containing a small amount of hydrogen fluoride with caesium iodide.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] This discovery caused the recognition that argon could form weakly bound compounds, even though it was not the first.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] It is stable up to 17 kelvins (−256 °C).
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The metastable ArCF2+ 2 dication, which is valence-isoelectronic with carbonyl fluoride and phosgene, was observed in 2010.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon-36, in the form of argon hydride (argonium) ions, has been detected in interstellar medium associated with the Crab Nebula supernova; this was the first noble-gas molecule detected in outer space.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Solid argon hydride (Ar(H2)2) has the same crystal structure as the MgZn2 Laves phase.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] It forms at pressures between 4.3 and 220 GPa, though Raman measurements suggest that the H2 molecules in Ar(H2)2 dissociate above 175 GPa.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is extracted industrially by the fractional distillation of liquid air in a cryogenic air separation unit; a process that separates liquid nitrogen, which boils at 77.3 K, from argon, which boils at 87.3 K, and liquid oxygen, which boils at 90.2 K.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] About 700,000 tonnes of argon are produced worldwide every year.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Other noble gases would be equally suitable for most of these applications, but argon is by far the cheapest.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] It is inexpensive, since it occurs naturally in air and is readily obtained as a byproduct of cryogenic air separation in the production of liquid oxygen and liquid nitrogen: the primary constituents of air are used on a large industrial scale.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The other noble gases (except helium) are produced this way as well, but argon is the most plentiful by far.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The bulk of its applications arise simply because it is inert and relatively cheap.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is used in some high-temperature industrial processes where ordinarily non-reactive substances become reactive.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] For example, an argon atmosphere is used in graphite electric furnaces to prevent the graphite from burning.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] For some of these processes, the presence of nitrogen or oxygen gases might cause defects within the material.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is used in some types of arc welding such as gas metal arc welding and gas tungsten arc welding, as well as in the processing of titanium and other reactive elements.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] An argon atmosphere is also used for growing crystals of silicon and germanium.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is used in the poultry industry to asphyxiate birds, either for mass culling following disease outbreaks, or as a means of slaughter more humane than electric stunning.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is denser than air and displaces oxygen close to the ground during inert gas asphyxiation.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Its non-reactive nature makes it suitable in a food product, and since it replaces oxygen within the dead bird, argon also enhances shelf life.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is sometimes used for extinguishing fires where valuable equipment may be damaged by water or foam.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Liquid argon is used as the target for neutrino experiments and direct dark matter searches.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The interaction between the hypothetical WIMPs and an argon nucleus produces scintillation light that is detected by photomultiplier tubes.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Two-phase detectors containing argon gas are used to detect the ionized electrons produced during the WIMP–nucleus scattering.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] As with most other liquefied noble gases, argon has a high scintillation light yield (about 51 photons/keV), is transparent to its own scintillation light, and is relatively easy to purify.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Compared to xenon, argon is cheaper and has a distinct scintillation time profile, which allows the separation of electronic recoils from nuclear recoils.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] On the other hand, its intrinsic beta-ray background is larger due to 39 Ar contamination, unless one uses argon from underground sources, which has much less 39 Ar contamination.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Most of the argon in Earth's atmosphere was produced by electron capture of long-lived 40 K (40 K + e− → 40 Ar + ν) present in natural potassium within Earth.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The 39 Ar activity in the atmosphere is maintained by cosmogenic production through the knockout reaction 40 Ar(n,2n)39 Ar and similar reactions.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The half-life of 39 Ar is only 269 years.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] As a result, the underground Ar, shielded by rock and water, has much less 39 Ar contamination.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Dark-matter detectors currently operating with liquid argon include DarkSide, WArP, ArDM, microCLEAN and DEAP.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Neutrino experiments include ICARUS and MicroBooNE, both of which use high-purity liquid argon in a time projection chamber for fine grained three-dimensional imaging of neutrino interactions.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] At Linköping University, Sweden, the inert gas is being utilized in a vacuum chamber in which plasma is introduced to ionize metallic films.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] This process results in a film usable for manufacturing computer processors.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The new process would eliminate the need for chemical baths and use of expensive, dangerous and rare materials.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is used to displace oxygen- and moisture-containing air in packaging material to extend the shelf-lives of the contents (argon has the European food additive code E938).
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Aerial oxidation, hydrolysis, and other chemical reactions that degrade the products are retarded or prevented entirely.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] High-purity chemicals and pharmaceuticals are sometimes packed and sealed in argon.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] In winemaking, argon is used in a variety of activities to provide a barrier against oxygen at the liquid surface, which can spoil wine by fueling both microbial metabolism (as with acetic acid bacteria) and standard redox chemistry.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is sometimes used as the propellant in aerosol cans.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is also used as a preservative for such products as varnish, polyurethane, and paint, by displacing air to prepare a container for storage.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Since 2002, the American National Archives stores important national documents such as the Declaration of Independence and the Constitution within argon-filled cases to inhibit their degradation.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is preferable to the helium that had been used in the preceding five decades, because helium gas escapes through the intermolecular pores in most containers and must be regularly replaced.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon may be used as the inert gas within Schlenk lines and gloveboxes.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is preferred to less expensive nitrogen in cases where nitrogen may react with the reagents or apparatus.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon may be used as the carrier gas in gas chromatography and in electrospray ionization mass spectrometry; it is the gas of choice for the plasma used in ICP spectroscopy.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is preferred for the sputter coating of specimens for scanning electron microscopy.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon gas is also commonly used for sputter deposition of thin films as in microelectronics and for wafer cleaning in microfabrication.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Cryosurgery procedures such as cryoablation use liquid argon to destroy tissue such as cancer cells.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] It is used in a procedure called "argon-enhanced coagulation", a form of argon plasma beam electrosurgery.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] The procedure carries a risk of producing gas embolism and has resulted in the death of at least one patient.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Blue argon lasers are used in surgery to weld arteries, destroy tumors, and correct eye defects.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon has also been used experimentally to replace nitrogen in the breathing or decompression mix known as Argox, to speed the elimination of dissolved nitrogen from the blood.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Incandescent lights are filled with argon, to preserve the filaments at high temperature from oxidation.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] It is used for the specific way it ionizes and emits light, such as in plasma globes and calorimetry in experimental particle physics.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Gas-discharge lamps filled with pure argon provide lilac/violet light; with argon and some mercury, blue light.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is also used for blue and green argon-ion lasers.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is used for thermal insulation in energy-efficient windows.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is also used in technical scuba diving to inflate a dry suit because it is inert and has low thermal conductivity.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon is used as a propellant in the development of the Variable Specific Impulse Magnetoplasma Rocket (VASIMR).
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Compressed argon gas is allowed to expand, to cool the seeker heads of some versions of the AIM-9 Sidewinder missile and other missiles that use cooled thermal seeker heads.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon-39, with a half-life of 269 years, has been used for a number of applications, primarily ice core and ground water dating.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Also, potassium–argon dating and related argon-argon dating are used to date sedimentary, metamorphic, and igneous rocks.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Argon has been used by athletes as a doping agent to simulate hypoxic conditions.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] In 2014, the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) added argon and xenon to the list of prohibited substances and methods, although at this time there is no reliable test for abuse.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] Although argon is non-toxic, it is 38% more dense than air and therefore considered a dangerous asphyxiant in closed areas.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] It is difficult to detect because it is colorless, odorless, and tasteless.
[src:buckingham-potential/argon] A 1994 incident, in which a man was asphyxiated after entering an argon-filled section of oil pipe under construction in Alaska, highlights the dangers of argon tank leakage in confined spaces and emphasizes the need for proper use, storage and handling.
[src:buckingham-potential/atomic-spacing] The atomic spacing of crystalline structures is usually determined by passing an electromagnetic wave of known frequency through the material, and using the laws of diffraction to determine its atomic spacing.
[src:buckingham-potential/atomic-spacing] The atomic spacing of amorphous materials (such as glass) varies substantially between different pairs of atoms, therefore diffraction cannot be used to accurately determine atomic spacing.
[src:buckingham-potential/atomic-spacing] In this case, the average bond length is a common way of expressing the distance between its atoms.
[src:buckingham-potential/atomic-spacing] Bond length can be determined between different elements in molecules by using the atomic radii of the atoms.
[src:buckingham-potential/atomic-spacing] Carbon bonds with itself to form two covalent network solids.
[src:buckingham-potential/atomic-spacing] Although both bonds are between the same pair of elements they can have different bond lengths.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] In theoretical chemistry, the **Buckingham potential** is a model of intermolecular interactions based on pair potentials developed by Richard Buckingham.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] The model describes repulsion by the Pauli exclusion principle and attraction by van der Waals forces between all atom pairs that are not directly bonded as a function of the interatomic distance r .
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] is given by two terms that represent the attraction and the repulsion, respectively.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] The constants, A , B , and C are parametrizations of the model tuned to the specific type of each atom pair.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] Buckingham proposed this as a simplification of the Lennard-Jones potential, in a theoretical study of the equation of state for gaseous helium, neon and argon.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] As explained in Buckingham's original paper and, e.g., in section 2.2.5 of Jensen's text, the repulsion is due to the interpenetration of the closed electron shells.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] "There is therefore some justification for choosing the repulsive part (of the potential) as an exponential function".
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] The Buckingham potential has been used extensively in simulations of molecular dynamics.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] Because the exponential term converges to a constant with decreasing distance, while the $r^{-6}$ term diverges, the Buckingham potential becomes attractive as r becomes small.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] This may be problematic when dealing with a structure with very short interatomic distances, as any nuclei that cross a certain threshold will become strongly (and unphysically) bound to one another at a distance of zero.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] The modified Buckingham potential, also called the "exp-six" potential, is used to calculate the interatomic forces for gases based on Chapman and Cowling collision theory.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] This potential function is only valid when $r>r_{max}$ , as the potential will decay towards $-\infty$ as $r\rightarrow 0$ .
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] This is corrected by identifying $r_{max}$ , which is the value of r at which the potential is maximized; when $r\leq {r_{max}}$ , the potential is set to infinity.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] The Coulomb–Buckingham potential is an extension of the Buckingham potential for application to ionic systems (e.g. ceramic materials).
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] where *A*, *B*, and *C* are suitable constants and the additional term is the electrostatic potential energy.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] where $r_{0}$ is the minimum energy distance, $\alpha$ is a free dimensionless parameter and $\varepsilon$ is the depth of the minimum energy.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] The BKS potential is a force field that may be used to simulate the interatomic potential between Silica glass atoms.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] Rather than relying only on experimental data, the BKS potential is derived by combining *ab initio* quantum chemistry methods on small silica clusters to describe accurate interaction between nearest-neighbors, which is the function of accurate force field.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] The experimental data is applied to fit larger scale force information beyond nearest neighbors.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] By combining the microscopic and macroscopic information, the applicability of the BKS potential has been extended to both the silica polymorphs and other tetrahedral network oxides systems that have same cluster structure, such as aluminophosphates, carbon and silicon.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] The form of this interatomic potential is the usual Buckingham form, with the addition of a Coulomb force term.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] where $\Phi _{ij}(r)$ is the interatomic potential between atom i and atom j , $q_{i}$ and $q_{j}$ are the charges magnitudes, $r_{ij}$ is the distance between atoms, and $A_{ij}$ , $B_{ij}$ and $C_{ij}$ are constant parameters based on the type of atoms.
[src:buckingham-potential/buckingham-potential] An updated version of the BKS potential introduced a new repulsive term to prevent atom overlapping.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon is the 15th most abundant element in the Earth's crust, and the fourth most abundant element in the universe by mass after hydrogen, helium, and oxygen.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon's abundance, its unique diversity of organic compounds, and its unusual ability to form polymers at the temperatures commonly encountered on Earth, enables it to serve as the common element of all known life.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] It is the second most abundant element in the human body by mass (about 18.5%) after oxygen.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The atoms of carbon can bond together in diverse ways, resulting in various allotropes of carbon.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Well-known allotropes include graphite, diamond, amorphous carbon, and fullerenes.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The physical properties of carbon vary widely with the allotropic form.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] For example, graphite is opaque and black, while diamond is highly transparent.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Graphite is soft enough to form a streak on paper (hence its name, from the Greek verb "γράφειν" which means "to write"), while diamond is the hardest naturally occurring material known.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Graphite is a good electrical conductor while diamond has a low electrical conductivity.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Under normal conditions, diamond, carbon nanotubes, and graphene have the highest thermal conductivities of all known materials.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] All carbon allotropes are solids under normal conditions, with graphite being the most thermodynamically stable form at standard temperature and pressure.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] They are chemically resistant and require high temperature to react even with oxygen.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The most common oxidation state of carbon in inorganic compounds is +4, while +2 is found in carbon monoxide and transition metal carbonyl complexes.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The largest sources of inorganic carbon are limestones, dolomites and carbon dioxide, but significant quantities occur in organic deposits of coal, peat, oil, and methane clathrates.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon forms a vast number of compounds, with about two hundred million having been described and indexed; and yet that number is still only a fraction of the number of theoretically possible compounds under standard conditions.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon in its solid state exists in several allotropes, including graphite, a soft, black, and slippery material, and diamond, the hardest naturally occurring substance.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] This variation in physical properties arises from differences in atomic arrangement: graphite consists of layers of hexagonally arranged carbon atoms, while diamond features a rigid three-dimensional lattice.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Chemically, carbon is notable for its ability to form stable chemical bonds with many elements, particularly with other carbon atoms, and is capable of forming multiple stable covalent bonds with suitable multivalent atoms.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon is a component element in the large majority of all chemical compounds, with about two hundred million examples having been described in the published chemical literature.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon also has the highest sublimation point of all elements.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Compared to its well-known solid allotropes, the liquid and gaseous phases of carbon are far less studied.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In the vapor phase, some of the carbon is in the form of highly reactive diatomic carbon (also known as dicarbon, with a chemical formula of C2).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The liquid phase of carbon is a dark, mobile, and reflective liquid that can only exist above 4,000 K (3,730 °C; 6,740 °F) and under pressures exceeding 100 atmospheres.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon is the sixth element, with a ground-state electron configuration of 1s22s22p2, of which the four outer electrons are valence electrons.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Its first four ionisation energies, 1086.5, 2352.6, 4620.5 and 6222.7 kJ/mol, are much higher than those of the heavier group-14 elements.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The electronegativity of carbon is 2.5, significantly higher than the heavier group-14 elements (1.8–1.9), but close to most of the nearby nonmetals, as well as some of the second- and third-row transition metals.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon's covalent radii are normally taken as 77.2 pm (C−C), 66.7 pm (C=C) and 60.3 pm (C≡C), although these may vary depending on coordination number and what the carbon is bonded to.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In general, covalent radius decreases with lower coordination number and higher bond order.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Graphite is much more reactive than diamond at standard conditions, despite being more thermodynamically stable, as its delocalised pi system is much more vulnerable to attack.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] For example, graphite can be oxidised by hot concentrated nitric acid at standard conditions to mellitic acid, C6(CO2H)6, which preserves the hexagonal units of graphite while breaking up the larger structure.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon-based compounds form the basis of all known life on Earth, and the carbon-nitrogen-oxygen cycle provides a small portion of the energy produced by the Sun, and most of the energy in larger stars (e.g.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Although it forms an extraordinary variety of compounds, most forms of carbon are comparatively unreactive under normal conditions.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] At standard temperature and pressure, it resists all but the strongest oxidizers.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] It does not react with sulfuric acid, hydrochloric acid, chlorine or any alkalis.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] At elevated temperatures, carbon reacts with oxygen to form carbon oxides and will rob oxygen from metal oxides to leave the elemental metal.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon combines with some metals at high temperatures to form metallic carbides, such as the iron carbide cementite in steel and tungsten carbide, widely used as an abrasive and for making hard tips for cutting tools.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Atomic carbon is a very short-lived species and, therefore, carbon is stabilized in various multi-atomic structures with diverse molecular configurations called allotropes.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The three relatively well-known allotropes of carbon are amorphous carbon, graphite, and diamond.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Once considered exotic, fullerenes are nowadays commonly synthesized and used in research; they include buckyballs, carbon nanotubes, carbon nanobuds and nanofibers.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Several other exotic allotropes have also been discovered, such as lonsdaleite, glassy carbon, carbon nanofoam and linear acetylenic carbon (carbyne).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Graphene is a two-dimensional sheet of carbon with the atoms arranged in a hexagonal lattice.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] As of 2009, graphene appears to be the strongest material ever tested.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The process of separating it from graphite will require some further technological development before it is economical for industrial processes.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] If successful, graphene could be used in the construction of a space elevator.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] It could also be used to safely store hydrogen for use in a hydrogen based engine in cars.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The amorphous form is an assortment of carbon atoms in a non-crystalline, irregular, glassy state, not held in a crystalline macrostructure.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] It is present as a powder, and is the main constituent of substances such as charcoal, lampblack (soot), and activated carbon.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] At normal pressures, carbon takes the form of graphite, in which each atom is bonded trigonally to three others in a plane composed of fused hexagonal rings, just like those in aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The resulting network is 2-dimensional, and the resulting flat sheets are stacked and loosely bonded through weak van der Waals forces.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] This gives graphite its softness and its cleaving properties (the sheets slip easily past one another).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Because of the delocalization of one of the outer electrons of each atom to form a π-cloud, graphite conducts electricity, but only in the plane of each covalently bonded sheet.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] This results in a lower bulk electrical conductivity for carbon than for most metals.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The delocalization also accounts for the energetic stability of graphite over diamond at room temperature.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] At very high pressures, carbon forms the more compact allotrope, diamond, having nearly twice the density of graphite.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Here, each atom is bonded tetrahedrally to four others, forming a 3-dimensional network of puckered six-membered rings of atoms.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Diamond has the same cubic structure as silicon and germanium, and because of the strength of the carbon-carbon bonds, it is the hardest naturally occurring substance measured by resistance to scratching.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Contrary to the popular belief that *"diamonds are forever"*, they are thermodynamically unstable (Δf*G*°(diamond, 298 K) = 2.9 kJ/mol) under normal conditions (298 K, 105 Pa) and should theoretically transform into graphite.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] But due to a high activation energy barrier, the transition into graphite is so slow at normal temperature that it is unnoticeable.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] However, at very high temperatures diamond will turn into graphite, and diamonds can burn up in a house fire.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The bottom left corner of the phase diagram for carbon has not been scrutinized experimentally.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Under some conditions, carbon crystallizes as lonsdaleite, a hexagonal crystal lattice with all atoms covalently bonded and properties similar to those of diamond.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Fullerenes are a synthetic crystalline formation with a graphite-like structure, but in place of flat hexagonal cells only, some of the cells of which fullerenes are formed may be pentagons, nonplanar hexagons, or even heptagons of carbon atoms.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The sheets are thus warped into spheres, ellipses, or cylinders.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The properties of fullerenes (split into buckyballs, buckytubes, and nanobuds) have not yet been fully analyzed and represent an intense area of research in nanomaterials.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The names *fullerene* and *buckyball* are given after Richard Buckminster Fuller, popularizer of geodesic domes, which resemble the structure of fullerenes.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The buckyballs are fairly large molecules formed completely of carbon bonded trigonally, forming spheroids (the best-known and simplest is the soccerball-shaped C60 buckminsterfullerene).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon nanotubes (buckytubes) are structurally similar to buckyballs, except that each atom is bonded trigonally in a curved sheet that forms a hollow cylinder.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Nanobuds were first reported in 2007 and are hybrid buckytube/buckyball materials (buckyballs are covalently bonded to the outer wall of a nanotube) that combine the properties of both in a single structure.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Of the other discovered allotropes, carbon nanofoam is a ferromagnetic allotrope discovered in 1997.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] It consists of a low-density cluster-assembly of carbon atoms strung together in a loose three-dimensional web, in which the atoms are bonded trigonally in six- and seven-membered rings.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] It is among the lightest known solids, with a density of about 2 kg/m3.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Similarly, glassy carbon contains a high proportion of closed porosity, but contrary to normal graphite, the graphitic layers are not stacked like pages in a book, but have a more random arrangement.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Linear acetylenic carbon has the chemical structure −(C≡C)n− .
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon in this modification is linear with *sp* orbital hybridization, and is a polymer with alternating single and triple bonds.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] This carbyne is of considerable interest to nanotechnology as its Young's modulus is 40 times that of the hardest known material – diamond.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In 2015, a team at the North Carolina State University announced the development of another allotrope they have dubbed Q-carbon, created by a high-energy low-duration laser pulse on amorphous carbon dust.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Q-carbon is reported to exhibit ferromagnetism, fluorescence, and a hardness superior to diamonds.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Isotopes of carbon are atomic nuclei that contain six protons plus a number of neutrons (varying from 2 to 16).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon has two stable, naturally occurring isotopes.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The isotope carbon-12 (12C) forms 98.93% of the carbon on Earth, while carbon-13 (13C) forms the remaining 1.07%.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The concentration of 12C is further increased in biological materials because biochemical reactions discriminate against 13C.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In 1961, the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) adopted the isotope carbon-12 as the basis for atomic weights.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Identification of carbon in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) experiments is done with the isotope 13C.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon-14 (14C) is a naturally occurring radioisotope, created in the upper atmosphere (lower stratosphere and upper troposphere) by interaction of nitrogen with cosmic rays.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] It is found in trace amounts on Earth of 1 part per trillion (0.0000000001%) or more, mostly confined to the atmosphere and superficial deposits, particularly of peat and other organic materials.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] This isotope decays by 0.158 MeV β− emission.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Because of its relatively short half-life of 5700±30 years, 14C is virtually absent in ancient rocks.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The amount of 14C in the atmosphere and in living organisms is almost constant, but decreases predictably in their bodies after death.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] This principle is used in radiocarbon dating, invented in 1949, which has been used extensively to determine the age of carbonaceous materials with ages up to about 40,000 years.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] There are 15 known isotopes of carbon and the shortest-lived of these is 8C which decays through proton emission and has a half-life of 3.5×10−21 s.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The exotic 19C exhibits a nuclear halo, which means its radius is appreciably larger than would be expected if the nucleus were a sphere of constant density.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon is the fourth most abundant chemical element in the observable universe by mass after hydrogen, helium, and oxygen.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Some meteorites contain microscopic diamonds that were formed when the Solar System was still a protoplanetary disk.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Microscopic diamonds may also be formed by the intense pressure and high temperature at the sites of meteorite impacts.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In 2014 NASA announced a greatly upgraded database for tracking polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs) in the universe.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] More than 20% of the carbon in the universe may be associated with PAHs, complex compounds of carbon and hydrogen without oxygen.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] These compounds figure in the PAH world hypothesis where they are hypothesized to have a role in abiogenesis and formation of life.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] PAHs seem to have been formed "a couple of billion years" after the Big Bang, are widespread throughout the universe, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] It has been estimated that the solid earth as a whole contains 730 ppm of carbon, with 2000 ppm in the core and 120 ppm in the combined mantle and crust.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Since the mass of the earth is 5.972×1024 kg, this would imply 4360 million gigatonnes of carbon.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] This is much more than the amount of carbon in the oceans or atmosphere (below).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In combination with oxygen in carbon dioxide, carbon is found in the Earth's atmosphere (approximately 900 gigatonnes of carbon — each ppm corresponds to 2.13 Gt) and dissolved in all water bodies (approximately 36,000 gigatonnes of carbon).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon in the biosphere has been estimated at 550 gigatonnes but with a large uncertainty, due mostly to a huge uncertainty in the amount of terrestrial deep subsurface bacteria.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Hydrocarbons (such as coal, petroleum, and natural gas) contain carbon as well.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Coal "reserves" (not "resources") amount to around 900 gigatonnes with perhaps 18,000 Gt of resources.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Proven sources of natural gas are about 175×1012 cubic metres (containing about 105 gigatonnes of carbon), but studies estimate another 900×1012 cubic metres of "unconventional" deposits such as shale gas, representing about 540 gigatonnes of carbon.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon is also found in methane hydrates in polar regions and under the seas.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Various estimates put this carbon between 500, 2500, or 3,000 Gt.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] According to one source, in the period from 1751 to 2008 about 347 gigatonnes of carbon were released as carbon dioxide to the atmosphere from burning of fossil fuels.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Another source puts the amount added to the atmosphere for the period since 1750 at 879 Gt, and the total going to the atmosphere, sea, and land (such as peat bogs) at almost 2,000 Gt.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon is a constituent (about 12% by mass) of the very large masses of carbonate rock (limestone, dolomite, marble, and others).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Coal is very rich in carbon (anthracite contains 92–98%) and is the largest commercial source of mineral carbon, accounting for 4,000 gigatonnes or 80% of fossil fuel.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] As for individual carbon allotropes, graphite is found in large quantities in China, Russia, Mexico, Canada, and India.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Natural diamonds occur in the rock kimberlite, found in ancient volcanic "necks", or "pipes".
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Most diamond deposits are in Africa, notably in South Africa, Namibia, Botswana, the Republic of the Congo, and Angola.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Diamond deposits have also been found in Arkansas, Canada, the Russian Arctic, Brazil, and in Northern and Western Australia.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Diamonds are found naturally, but about 90% of all industrial diamonds used in the U.S. are now manufactured.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon-14 is formed in upper layers of the troposphere and the stratosphere at altitudes of 9–15 km by a reaction that is precipitated by cosmic rays.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Thermal neutrons are produced that collide with the nuclei of nitrogen-14, forming carbon-14 and a proton.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] As such, 1.5%×10−10 of atmospheric carbon dioxide contains carbon-14.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon-rich asteroids are relatively preponderant in the outer parts of the asteroid belt in the Solar System.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] These asteroids have not yet been directly sampled by scientists.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The asteroids can be used in hypothetical space-based carbon mining, which may be possible in the future, but is currently technologically impossible.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Formation of the carbon atomic nucleus occurs within a giant or supergiant star through the triple-alpha process.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The triple-alpha process happens in conditions of temperatures over 100 megakelvins and helium concentration that the rapid expansion and cooling of the early universe prohibited, and therefore no significant carbon was created during the Big Bang.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] According to current physical cosmology theory, carbon is formed in the interiors of stars on the horizontal branch.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] When massive stars die as supernova, the carbon is scattered into space as dust.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] This dust becomes component material for the formation of the next-generation star systems with accreted planets.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The Solar System is one such star system with an abundance of carbon, enabling the existence of life as we know it.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] It is the opinion of most scholars that all the carbon in the Solar System and the Milky Way comes from dying stars.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The CNO cycle is an additional hydrogen fusion mechanism that powers stars, wherein carbon operates as a catalyst.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Rotational transitions of various isotopic forms of carbon monoxide (for example, 12CO, 13CO, and 18CO) are detectable in the submillimeter wavelength range, and are used in the study of newly forming stars in molecular clouds.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Under terrestrial conditions, conversion of one element to another is very rare.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Therefore, the amount of carbon on Earth is effectively constant.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Thus, processes that use carbon must obtain it from somewhere and dispose of it somewhere else.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The paths of carbon in the environment form the carbon cycle.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] For example, photosynthetic plants draw carbon dioxide from the atmosphere (or seawater) and build it into biomass, as in the Calvin cycle, a process of carbon fixation.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Some of this biomass is eaten by animals, while some carbon is exhaled by animals as carbon dioxide.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The carbon cycle is considerably more complicated than this short loop; for example, some carbon dioxide is dissolved in the oceans; if bacteria do not consume it, dead plant or animal matter may become petroleum or coal, which releases carbon when burned.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon can form very long chains of interconnecting carbon–carbon bonds, a property that is called catenation.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon-carbon bonds are strong and stable.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Through catenation, carbon forms a countless number of compounds.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] A tally of unique compounds shows that more contain carbon than do not.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The simplest form of an organic molecule is the hydrocarbon—a large family of organic molecules that are composed of hydrogen atoms bonded to a chain of carbon atoms.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] A hydrocarbon backbone can be substituted by other atoms, known as heteroatoms.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Common heteroatoms that appear in organic compounds include oxygen, nitrogen, sulfur, phosphorus, and the nonradioactive halogens, as well as the metals lithium and magnesium.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Organic compounds containing bonds to metal are known as organometallic compounds (*see below*).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Certain groupings of atoms, often including heteroatoms, recur in large numbers of organic compounds.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] These collections, known as *functional groups*, confer common reactivity patterns and allow for the systematic study and categorization of organic compounds.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Chain length, shape and functional groups all affect the properties of organic molecules.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In most stable compounds of carbon (and nearly all stable *organic* compounds), carbon obeys the octet rule and is *tetravalent*, meaning that a carbon atom forms a total of four covalent bonds (which may include double and triple bonds).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon occurs in all known organic life and is the basis of organic chemistry.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] When united with hydrogen, it forms various hydrocarbons that are important to industry as refrigerants, lubricants, solvents, as chemical feedstock for the manufacture of plastics and petrochemicals, and as fossil fuels.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] When combined with oxygen and hydrogen, carbon can form many groups of important biological compounds including sugars, lignans, chitins, alcohols, fats, aromatic esters, carotenoids and terpenes.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] With nitrogen, it forms alkaloids, and with the addition of sulfur also it forms antibiotics, amino acids, and rubber products.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] With the addition of phosphorus to these other elements, it forms DNA and RNA, the chemical-code carriers of life, and adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the most important energy-transfer molecule in all living cells.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Norman Horowitz, head of the Mariner and Viking missions to Mars (1965–1976), considered that the unique characteristics of carbon made it unlikely that any other element could replace carbon, even on another planet, to generate the biochemistry necessary for life.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Among these are the simple oxides of carbon.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The most prominent oxide is carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] This was once the principal constituent of the paleoatmosphere, but is a minor component of the Earth's atmosphere today.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Dissolved in water, it forms carbonic acid (H 2CO 3), but as most compounds with multiple single-bonded oxygens on a single carbon it is unstable.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Through this intermediate, though, resonance-stabilized carbonate ions are produced.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Some important minerals are carbonates, notably calcite.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The other common oxide is carbon monoxide (CO).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] It is formed by incomplete combustion, and is a colorless, odorless gas.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The molecules each contain a triple bond and are fairly polar, resulting in a tendency to bind permanently to hemoglobin molecules, displacing oxygen, which has a lower binding affinity.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Cyanide (CN−) has a similar structure, but behaves much like a halide ion (pseudohalogen).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] For example, it can form the nitride cyanogen molecule ((CN)2), similar to diatomic halides.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Likewise, the heavier analog of cyanide, cyaphide (CP−), is also considered inorganic, though most simple derivatives are highly unstable.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Other uncommon oxides are carbon suboxide (C 3O 2), the unstable dicarbon monoxide (C2O), carbon trioxide (CO3), cyclopentanepentone (C5O5), cyclohexanehexone (C6O6), and mellitic anhydride (C12O9).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] However, mellitic anhydride is the triple acyl anhydride of mellitic acid; moreover, it contains a benzene ring.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Thus, many chemists consider it to be organic.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] With reactive metals, such as tungsten, carbon forms either carbides (C4−) or acetylides (C2− 2) to form alloys with high melting points.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] These anions are also associated with methane and acetylene, both very weak acids.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] With an electronegativity of 2.5, carbon prefers to form covalent bonds.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] A few carbides are covalent lattices, like carborundum (SiC), which resembles diamond.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Nevertheless, even the most polar and salt-like of carbides are not completely ionic compounds.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Organometallic compounds by definition contain at least one carbon-metal covalent bond.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Many metal carbonyls and metal cyanides exist (for example, tetracarbonylnickel and potassium ferricyanide); some workers consider metal carbonyl and cyanide complexes without other carbon ligands to be purely inorganic, and not organometallic.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] However, most organometallic chemists consider metal complexes with any carbon ligand, even 'inorganic carbon' (e.g., carbonyls, cyanides, and certain types of carbides and acetylides) to be organometallic in nature.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Metal complexes containing organic ligands without a carbon-metal covalent bond (e.g., metal carboxylates) are termed *metalorganic* compounds.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] While carbon is understood to strongly prefer formation of four covalent bonds, other exotic bonding schemes are also known.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carboranes are highly stable dodecahedral derivatives of the [B12H12]2- unit, with one BH replaced with a CH+.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Thus, the carbon is bonded to five boron atoms and one hydrogen atom.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The cation [(Ph3PAu)6C]2+ contains an octahedral carbon bound to six phosphine-gold fragments.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] This phenomenon has been attributed to the aurophilicity of the gold ligands, which provide additional stabilization of an otherwise labile species.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In nature, the iron-molybdenum cofactor (FeMoco) responsible for microbial nitrogen fixation likewise has an octahedral carbon center (formally a carbide, C(-IV)) bonded to six iron atoms.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In 2016, it was confirmed that, in line with earlier theoretical predictions, the hexamethylbenzene dication contains a carbon atom with six bonds.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] More specifically, the dication could be described structurally by the formulation [MeC(η5-C5Me5)]2+, making it an "organic metallocene" in which a MeC3+ fragment is bonded to a η5-C5Me5− fragment through all five of the carbons of the ring.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In the cases above, each of the bonds to carbon contain less than two formal electron pairs.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Thus, the formal electron count of these species does not exceed an octet.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] This makes them hypercoordinate but not hypervalent.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The English name *carbon* comes from the Latin *carbo* for coal and charcoal, whence also comes the French *charbon*, meaning charcoal.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In German, Dutch and Danish, the names for carbon are *Kohlenstoff*, *koolstof*, and *kulstof* respectively, all literally meaning coal-substance.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon was discovered in prehistory and was known in the forms of soot and charcoal to the earliest human civilizations.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Diamonds were known probably as early as 2500 BCE in China, while carbon in the form of charcoal was made by the same chemistry as it is today, by heating wood in a pyramid covered with clay to exclude air.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In 1722, René Antoine Ferchault de Réaumur demonstrated that iron was transformed into steel through the absorption of some substance, now known to be carbon.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In 1772, Antoine Lavoisier showed that diamonds are a form of carbon; when he burned samples of charcoal and diamond and found that neither produced any water and that both released the same amount of carbon dioxide per gram.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In 1779, Carl Wilhelm Scheele showed that graphite, which had been thought of as a form of lead, was instead identical with charcoal but with a small admixture of iron, and that it gave "aerial acid" (his name for carbon dioxide) when oxidized with nitric acid.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In 1786, the French scientists Claude Louis Berthollet, Gaspard Monge and C.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Vandermonde confirmed that graphite was mostly carbon by oxidizing it in oxygen in much the same way Lavoisier had done with diamond.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Some iron again was left, which the French scientists thought was necessary to the graphite structure.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In their publication they proposed the name *carbone* (Latin *carbonum*) for the element in graphite which was given off as a gas upon burning graphite.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Antoine Lavoisier then listed carbon as an element in his 1789 textbook.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] A new allotrope of carbon, fullerene, that was discovered in 1985 includes nanostructured forms such as buckyballs and nanotubes.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Their discoverers – Robert Curl, Harold Kroto, and Richard Smalley – received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1996.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The resulting renewed interest in new forms led to the discovery of further exotic allotropes, including glassy carbon, and the realization that "amorphous carbon" is not strictly amorphous.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Commercially viable natural deposits of graphite occur in many parts of the world, but the most important sources economically are in China, India, Brazil, and North Korea.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Graphite deposits are of metamorphic origin, found in association with quartz, mica, and feldspars in schists, gneisses, and metamorphosed sandstones and limestone as lenses or veins, sometimes of a metre or more in thickness.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Deposits of graphite in Borrowdale, Cumberland, England were at first of sufficient size and purity that, until the 19th century, pencils were made by sawing blocks of natural graphite into strips before encasing the strips in wood.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Today, smaller deposits of graphite are obtained by crushing the parent rock and floating the lighter graphite out on water.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] There are three types of natural graphite—amorphous, flake or crystalline flake, and vein or lump.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Amorphous graphite is the lowest quality and most abundant.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Contrary to science, in industry "amorphous" refers to very small crystal size rather than complete lack of crystal structure.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Amorphous is used for lower value graphite products and is the lowest priced graphite.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Large amorphous graphite deposits are found in China, Europe, Mexico and the United States.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Flake graphite is less common and of higher quality than amorphous; it occurs as separate plates that crystallized in metamorphic rock.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Flake graphite can be four times the price of amorphous.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Good quality flakes can be processed into expandable graphite for many uses, such as flame retardants.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The foremost deposits are found in Austria, Brazil, Canada, China, Germany and Madagascar.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Vein or lump graphite is the rarest, most valuable, and highest quality type of natural graphite.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] It occurs in veins along intrusive contacts in solid lumps, and it is only commercially mined in Sri Lanka.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] According to the USGS, world production of natural graphite was 1.1 million tonnes in 2010, to which China contributed 800,000 t, India 130,000 t, Brazil 76,000 t, North Korea 30,000 t and Canada 25,000 t.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] No natural graphite was reported mined in the United States, but 118,000 t of synthetic graphite with an estimated value of $998 million was produced in 2009.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The diamond supply chain is controlled by a limited number of powerful businesses, and is also highly concentrated in a small number of locations around the world (see figure).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Only a very small fraction of the diamond ore consists of actual diamonds.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The ore is crushed, during which care has to be taken in order to prevent larger diamonds from being destroyed in this process and subsequently the particles are sorted by density.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Today, diamonds are located in the diamond-rich density fraction with the help of X-ray fluorescence, after which the final sorting steps are done by hand.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Before the use of X-rays became commonplace, the separation was done with grease belts; diamonds have a stronger tendency to stick to grease than the other minerals in the ore.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Historically diamonds were known to be found only in alluvial deposits in southern India.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Diamond production of primary deposits (kimberlites and lamproites) only started in the 1870s after the discovery of the diamond fields in South Africa.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Production has increased over time and an accumulated total of over 4.5 billion carats have been mined since that date.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Most commercially viable diamond deposits were in Russia, Botswana, Australia and the Democratic Republic of Congo.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] By 2005, Russia produced almost one-fifth of the global diamond output (mostly in Yakutia territory; for example, Mir pipe and Udachnaya pipe) but the Argyle mine in Australia became the single largest source, producing 14 million carats in 2018.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] New finds, the Canadian mines at Diavik and Ekati, are expected to become even more valuable owing to their production of gem quality stones.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In the United States, diamonds have been found in Arkansas, Colorado, and Montana.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In 2004, a startling discovery of a microscopic diamond in the United States led to the January 2008 bulk-sampling of kimberlite pipes in a remote part of Montana.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] While natural diamonds form over time deep within the Earth, synthetic diamonds are created in laboratories through a variety of methods.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The original method uses high pressure and high temperature (HPHT) and is still widely used because of its relatively low cost.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The process involves large presses that can weigh hundreds of tons to produce a pressure of 5 GPa (730,000 psi) at 1,500 °C (2,730 °F).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The second method, using chemical vapor deposition (CVD), creates a carbon plasma over a substrate onto which the carbon atoms deposit to form diamond.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Other methods include explosive formation (forming detonation nanodiamonds) and sonication of graphite solutions.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon is essential to all known living systems, and without it life as we know it could not exist (see alternative biochemistry).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The major economic use of carbon other than food and wood is in the form of hydrocarbons, most notably the greenhouse gas and fossil fuel methane gas and crude oil (petroleum).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Crude oil is distilled in refineries by the petrochemical industry to produce gasoline, kerosene, and other products.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Cellulose is a natural, carbon-containing polymer produced by plants in the form of wood, cotton, linen, and hemp.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Cellulose is used primarily for maintaining structure in plants.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Commercially valuable carbon polymers of animal origin include wool, cashmere, and silk.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Plastics are made from synthetic carbon polymers, often with oxygen and nitrogen atoms included at regular intervals in the main polymer chain.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The raw materials for many of these synthetic substances come from crude oil and coal.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The uses of carbon and its compounds are extremely varied.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] It can form alloys with iron, of which the most common is carbon steel.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Graphite is combined with clays to form the 'lead' used in pencils used for writing and drawing.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] It is also used as a lubricant and a pigment, as a moulding material in glass manufacture, in electrodes for dry batteries and in electroplating and electroforming, in brushes for electric motors, and as a neutron moderator in nuclear reactors.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Charcoal is used as a drawing material in artwork, barbecue grilling, iron smelting, and in many other applications.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Wood, coal and oil are used as fuel for production of energy and heating.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Gem quality diamond is used in jewelry, and industrial diamonds are used in drilling, cutting and polishing tools for machining metals and stone.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon fiber, which is produced by pyrolyzing synthetic polyester fibers, is used to reinforce plastics, creating advanced, lightweight composite materials.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon fiber is made by pyrolysis of extruded and stretched filaments of polyacrylonitrile (PAN) and other organic substances.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The crystallographic structure and mechanical properties of the fiber depend on the type of starting material, and on the subsequent processing.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon fibers made from PAN have structure resembling narrow filaments of graphite, but thermal processing may re-order the structure into a continuous rolled sheet.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The result is fibers with higher specific tensile strength than steel.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon black is used as the black pigment in printing ink, artist's oil paint, and water colours, carbon paper, automotive finishes, India ink and laser printer toner.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon black is also used as a filler in rubber products such as tyres and in plastic compounds.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Activated charcoal is used as an absorbent and adsorbent in filter material in applications as diverse as gas masks, water purification, and kitchen extractor hoods, and in medicine to absorb toxins, poisons, or gases from the digestive system.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon is used in chemical reduction at high temperatures.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Coke is used to reduce iron ore into iron (smelting).
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Case hardening of steel is achieved by heating finished steel components in carbon powder.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbides of silicon, tungsten, boron, and titanium are among the hardest known materials, and are used as abrasives in cutting and grinding tools.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon compounds make up most of the materials used in clothing, such as natural and synthetic textiles and leather, and almost all of the interior surfaces in the built environment other than glass, stone, drywall, and metal.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The diamond industry falls into two categories: one dealing with gem-grade diamonds and the other, with industrial-grade diamonds.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] While a large trade in both types of diamonds exists, the two markets function dramatically differently.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Unlike precious metals such as gold or platinum, gem diamonds do not trade as a commodity.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] There is a substantial mark-up in the sale of diamonds, and there is not a very active market for resale of diamonds.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Industrial diamonds are valued mostly for their hardness and heat conductivity, with the gemological qualities of clarity and color being mostly irrelevant.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] About 80% of mined diamonds (equal to about 100 million carats or 20 tonnes annually) are unsuitable for use as gemstones and relegated for industrial use (known as *bort)*.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Synthetic diamonds, invented in the 1950s, found almost immediate industrial applications; 3 billion carats (600 tonnes) of synthetic diamond is produced annually.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The dominant industrial use of diamond is in cutting, drilling, grinding, and polishing.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Most of these applications do not require large diamonds; in fact, most diamonds of gem-quality except for their small size can be used industrially.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Diamonds are embedded in drill tips or saw blades, or ground into a powder for use in grinding and polishing applications.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Specialized applications include use in laboratories as containment for high-pressure experiments (see diamond anvil cell), high-performance bearings, and limited use in specialized windows.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] With the continuing advances in the production of synthetic diamonds, new applications are becoming feasible.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Garnering much excitement is the possible use of diamond as a semiconductor suitable for microchips, and because of its exceptional heat conductance property, as a heat sink in electronics.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Pure carbon has extremely low toxicity to humans and can be handled safely in the form of graphite or charcoal.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] It is resistant to dissolution or chemical attack, even in the acidic contents of the digestive tract.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Consequently, once it enters into the body's tissues it is likely to remain there indefinitely.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon black was probably one of the first pigments to be used for tattooing, and Ötzi the Iceman was found to have carbon tattoos that survived during his life and for 5200 years after his death.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Inhalation of coal dust or soot (carbon black) in large quantities can be dangerous, irritating lung tissues and causing the congestive lung disease, coalworker's pneumoconiosis.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Diamond dust used as an abrasive can be harmful if ingested or inhaled.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Microparticles of carbon are produced in diesel engine exhaust fumes, and may accumulate in the lungs.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] However, in these examples, the harm may result from contaminants (e.g., organic chemicals, heavy metals) rather than from the carbon itself.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Carbon may burn vigorously and brightly in the presence of air at high temperatures.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Large accumulations of coal, which have remained inert for hundreds of millions of years in the absence of oxygen, may spontaneously combust when exposed to air in coal mine waste tips, ship cargo holds and coal bunkers, and storage dumps.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] In nuclear applications where graphite is used as a neutron moderator, accumulation of Wigner energy followed by a sudden, spontaneous release may occur.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] Annealing to at least 250 °C can release the energy safely, although in the Windscale fire the procedure went wrong, causing other reactor materials to combust.
[src:buckingham-potential/carbon] The great variety of carbon compounds include such lethal poisons as tetrodotoxin, the lectin ricin from seeds of the castor oil plant *Ricinus communis*, cyanide (CN−), and carbon monoxide; and such essentials to life as glucose and protein.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] A **ceramic** is any of the various hard, brittle, heat-resistant, and corrosion-resistant materials made by shaping and then firing an inorganic, nonmetallic material, such as clay, at a high temperature.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Common examples are earthenware, porcelain, and brick.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The earliest ceramics made by humans were fired clay bricks used for building house walls and other structures.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Other pottery objects such as pots, vessels, vases and figurines were made from clay, either by itself or mixed with other materials like silica, hardened by sintering in fire.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Later, ceramics were glazed and fired to create smooth, colored surfaces, decreasing porosity through the use of glassy, amorphous ceramic coatings on top of the crystalline ceramic substrates.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramics now include domestic, industrial, and building products, as well as a wide range of materials developed for use in advanced ceramic engineering, such as semiconductors.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The word *ceramic* comes from the Ancient Greek word κεραμικός (*keramikós*), meaning "of or for pottery" (from κέραμος*(*kéramos*)* 'potter's clay, tile, pottery').
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The earliest known mention of the root *ceram-* is the Mycenaean Greek *ke-ra-me-we*, workers of ceramic, written in Linear B syllabic script.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The word *ceramic* can be used as an adjective to describe a material, product, or process, or it may be used as a noun, either singular or, more commonly, as the plural noun *ceramics*.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramic material is an inorganic, metallic oxide, nitride, or carbide material.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Some elements, such as carbon or silicon, may be considered ceramics.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramic materials are brittle, hard, strong in compression, and weak in shearing and tension.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] They withstand the chemical erosion that occurs in other materials subjected to acidic or caustic environments.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramics generally can withstand very high temperatures, ranging from 1,000 °C to 1,600 °C (1,800 °F to 3,000 °F).
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The crystallinity of ceramic materials varies widely.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Most often, fired ceramics are either vitrified or semi-vitrified, as is the case with earthenware, stoneware, and porcelain.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Varying crystallinity and electron composition in the ionic and covalent bonds cause most ceramic materials to be good thermal and electrical insulators (researched in ceramic engineering).
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Composites such as fiberglass and carbon fiber, while containing ceramic materials, are not considered to be part of the ceramic family.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Highly oriented crystalline ceramic materials are not amenable to a great range of processing.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Methods for dealing with them tend to fall into one of two categories: either making the ceramic in the desired shape by reaction *in situ* or "forming" powders into the desired shape and then sintering to form a solid body.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramic forming techniques include shaping by hand (sometimes including a rotation process called "throwing"), slip casting, tape casting (used for making very thin ceramic capacitors), injection molding, dry pressing, and other variations.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Many ceramics experts do not consider materials with an amorphous (noncrystalline) character (i.e., glass) to be ceramics, even though glassmaking involves several steps of the ceramic process and its mechanical properties are similar to those of ceramic materials.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] However, heat treatments can convert glass into a semi-crystalline material known as glass-ceramic.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Traditional ceramic raw materials include clay minerals such as kaolinite, whereas more recent materials include aluminium oxide, more commonly known as alumina.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Modern ceramic materials, which are classified as advanced ceramics, include silicon carbide and tungsten carbide.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Both are valued for their abrasion resistance and are therefore used in applications such as the wear plates of crushing equipment in mining operations.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Advanced ceramics are also used in the medical, electrical, electronics, and armor industries.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Human beings appear to have been making their own ceramics for at least 26,000 years, subjecting clay and silica to intense heat to fuse and form ceramic materials.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The earliest found so far were in southern central Europe and were sculpted figures, not dishes.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The earliest known pottery was made by mixing animal products with clay and firing it at up to 800 °C (1,500 °F).
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] While pottery fragments have been found up to 19,000 years old, it was not until about 10,000 years later that regular pottery became common.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] An early people that spread across much of Europe is named after its use of pottery: the Corded Ware culture.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] These early Indo-European peoples decorated their pottery by wrapping it with rope while it was still wet.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] When the ceramics were fired, the rope burned off but left a decorative pattern of complex grooves on the surface.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The invention of the wheel eventually led to the production of smoother, more even pottery using the wheel-forming (throwing) technique, like the pottery wheel.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Early ceramics were porous, absorbing water easily.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] It became useful for more items with the discovery of glazing techniques, which involved coating pottery with silicon, bone ash, or other materials that could melt and reform into a glassy surface, making a vessel less pervious to water.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramic artifacts have an important role in archaeology for understanding the culture, technology, and behavior of peoples of the past.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] They are among the most common artifacts to be found at an archaeological site, generally in the form of small fragments of broken pottery called sherds.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The processing of collected sherds can be consistent with two main types of analysis: technical and traditional.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The traditional analysis involves sorting ceramic artifacts, sherds, and larger fragments into specific types based on style, composition, manufacturing, and morphology.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] By creating these typologies, it is possible to distinguish between different cultural styles, the purpose of the ceramic, and the technological state of the people, among other conclusions.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Besides, by looking at stylistic changes in ceramics over time, it is possible to separate (seriate) the ceramics into distinct diagnostic groups (assemblages).
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] A comparison of ceramic artifacts with known dated assemblages allows for a chronological assignment of these pieces.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The technical approach to ceramic analysis involves a finer examination of the composition of ceramic artifacts and sherds to determine the source of the material and, through this, the possible manufacturing site.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Key criteria are the composition of the clay and the temper used in the manufacture of the article under study: the temper is a material added to the clay during the initial production stage and is used to aid the subsequent drying process.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Types of temper include shell pieces, granite fragments, and ground sherd pieces called 'grog'.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Temper is usually identified by microscopic examination of the tempered material.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Clay identification is determined by a process of refiring the ceramic and assigning a color to it using Munsell Soil Color notation.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] By estimating both the clay and temper compositions and locating a region where both are known to occur, an assignment of the material source can be made.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Based on the source assignment of the artifact, further investigations can be made into the site of manufacture.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The physical properties of any ceramic substance are a direct result of its crystalline structure and chemical composition.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramography is the art and science of preparation, examination, and evaluation of ceramic microstructures.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Evaluation and characterization of ceramic microstructures are often implemented on similar spatial scales to that used commonly in the emerging field of nanotechnology: from nanometers to tens of micrometers (μm).
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] This is typically somewhere between the minimum wavelength of visible light and the resolution limit of the naked eye.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The microstructure includes most grains, secondary phases, grain boundaries, pores, micro-cracks, structural defects, and hardness micro indentions.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Most bulk mechanical, optical, thermal, electrical, and magnetic properties are significantly affected by the observed microstructure.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The fabrication method and process conditions are generally indicated by the microstructure.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The root cause of many ceramic failures is evident in the cleaved and polished microstructure.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Mechanical properties are important in structural and building materials as well as textile fabrics.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] In modern materials science, fracture mechanics is an important tool in improving the mechanical performance of materials and components.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] It applies the physics of stress and strain, in particular the theories of elasticity and plasticity, to the microscopic crystallographic defects found in real materials in order to predict the macroscopic mechanical failure of bodies.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Fractography is widely used with fracture mechanics to understand the causes of failures and also verify the theoretical failure predictions with real-life failures.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramic materials are usually ionic or covalent bonded materials.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] A material held together by either type of bond will tend to fracture before any plastic deformation takes place, which results in poor toughness and brittle behavior in these materials.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Additionally, because these materials tend to be porous, pores and other microscopic imperfections act as stress concentrators, decreasing the toughness further, and reducing the tensile strength.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] These combine to give catastrophic failures, as opposed to the more ductile failure modes of metals.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] These materials do show plastic deformation.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] However, because of the rigid structure of crystalline material, there are very few available slip systems for dislocations to move, and so they deform very slowly.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] To overcome the brittle behavior, ceramic material development has introduced the class of ceramic matrix composite materials, in which ceramic fibers are embedded and with specific coatings form fiber bridges across any crack.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] This mechanism substantially increases the fracture toughness of such ceramics.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramic disc brakes are an example of using a ceramic matrix composite material manufactured with a specific process.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Scientists are working on developing ceramic materials that can withstand significant deformation without breaking.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] A first such material that can deform in room temperature was found in 2024.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Many strategies are employed to improve the toughness of ceramics to prevent fracture.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] This includes crack deflection, microcrack toughening, crack bridging, incorporation of ductile particles, and transformation toughening.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Crack deflection is a toughening mechanism that involves deflecting cracks away from more rapid crack propagation paths, preventing catastrophic sudden failure.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Cracks may be deflected using microstructures such as whiskers, as in the use of silicon carbide whiskers to reinforce molybdenum disilicide ceramic material detailed in a 1987 paper.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Crack deflecting second phases may also take the form of platelets, particles, or fibers.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Microcrack toughening involves nucleation (creation) of microcracks near a macroscopic crack tip where the crack propagates, which lowers the stress experienced by the tip and therefore the urgency of crack propagation.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] To improve toughness, second phase particles can be incorporated into ceramic such that they are subject to microcracking, which relieves stress to prevent fracture.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Crack bridging occurs when a strong discontinuous reinforcing phase applies a force behind the propagating tip of the crack that discourages further cracking.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] These second phase bridges essentially pin the crack to discourage its extension.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Crack bridging can be used to improve toughness via the incorporation of second phase whiskers in the ceramic, as well as other shapes, to bridge cracks.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ductile particle ceramic matrix composites are composed of ductile particles such as metals distributed in a ceramic matrix.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] These particles boost toughness by deforming plastically to absorb energy, and by bridging advancing cracks.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] To be most effective, the particles should be isolated from each other.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The most studied iterations of these composites consist of an alumina matrix, and nickel, iron, molybdenum, copper, or silver metal particles.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Transformation toughening occurs when a material undergoes stress-induced phase transformation.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Some ceramics are capable of undergoing stress-induced martensitic transformation, which involves an energy barrier that must be overcome by absorbing energy.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Martensitic transformations are diffusionless shear transformations involving the transition between an "austenite" or "parent" phase that is stable at higher temperatures and a "martensitic" phase that is stable at lower temperatures.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Because the transformation absorbs energy, stress-induced martensitic transformations can hinder crack progression and increases toughness.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] A key example of this phenomenon is zirconia, whose martensitic transformation involves a crystal structure transformation from a tetragonal crystal structure (the austenite phase) to a monoclinic structure.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The volume increase associated with transformation from tetragonal to monoclinic also relieves tensile stress at the crack, tip, further discouraging cracking and increasing toughness.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] When zirconia particles in a ceramic matrix undergo transformation during fabrication due to cooling, the stress fields around the particles lead to nucleation and extension of microcracks, which can also improve toughness of the material.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] These stress fields, as well as the particles themselves, can also contribute to crack deflection.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] If a ceramic is subjected to substantial mechanical loading, it can undergo a process called ice-templating, which allows some control of the microstructure of the ceramic product and therefore some control of the mechanical properties.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramic engineers use this technique to tune the mechanical properties to their desired application.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Specifically, the strength is increased when this technique is employed.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ice templating allows the creation of macroscopic pores in a unidirectional arrangement.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The applications of this oxide strengthening technique are important for solid oxide fuel cells and water filtration devices.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] To process a sample through ice templating, an aqueous colloidal suspension is prepared to contain the dissolved ceramic powder evenly dispersed throughout the colloid, for example yttria-stabilized zirconia (YSZ).
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The solution is then cooled from the bottom to the top on a platform that allows for unidirectional cooling.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The sample is then heated and at the same the pressure is reduced enough to force the ice crystals to sublime and the YSZ pockets begin to anneal together to form macroscopically aligned ceramic microstructures.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The sample is then further sintered to complete the evaporation of the residual water and the final consolidation of the ceramic microstructure.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] During ice-templating, a few variables can be controlled to influence the pore size and morphology of the microstructure.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] These important variables are the initial solids loading of the colloid, the cooling rate, the sintering temperature and duration, and the use of certain additives which can influence the microstructural morphology during the process.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] A good understanding of these parameters is essential to understanding the relationships between processing, microstructure, and mechanical properties of anisotropically porous materials.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Most of these are transition metal oxides that are II-VI semiconductors, such as zinc oxide.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] While there are prospects of mass-producing blue light-emitting diodes (LED) from zinc oxide, ceramicists are most interested in the electrical properties that show grain boundary effects.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] One of the most widely used of these is the varistor.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] These are devices that exhibit the property that resistance drops sharply at a certain threshold voltage.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Once the voltage across the device reaches the threshold, there is a breakdown of the electrical structure in the vicinity of the grain boundaries, which results in its electrical resistance dropping from several megohms down to a few hundred ohms.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The major advantage of these is that they can dissipate a lot of energy, and they self-reset; after the voltage across the device drops below the threshold, its resistance returns to being high.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] This makes them ideal for surge-protection applications; as there is control over the threshold voltage and energy tolerance, they find use in all sorts of applications.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The best demonstration of their ability can be found in electrical substations, where they are employed to protect the infrastructure from lightning strikes.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] They have rapid response, are low maintenance, and do not appreciably degrade from use, making them virtually ideal devices for this application.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Semiconducting ceramics are also employed as gas sensors.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] When various gases are passed over a polycrystalline ceramic, its electrical resistance changes.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] With tuning to the possible gas mixtures, very inexpensive devices can be produced.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Under some conditions, such as extremely low temperatures, some ceramics exhibit high-temperature superconductivity (in superconductivity, "high temperature" means above 30 K).
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The reason for this is not understood, but there are two major families of superconducting ceramics.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Piezoelectricity, a link between electrical and mechanical response, is exhibited by a large number of ceramic materials, including the quartz used to measure time in watches and other electronics.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Such devices use both properties of piezoelectrics, using electricity to produce a mechanical motion (powering the device) and then using this mechanical motion to produce electricity (generating a signal).
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The unit of time measured is the natural interval required for electricity to be converted into mechanical energy and back again.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The piezoelectric effect is generally stronger in materials that also exhibit pyroelectricity, and all pyroelectric materials are also piezoelectric.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] These materials can be used to inter-convert between thermal, mechanical, or electrical energy; for instance, after synthesis in a furnace, a pyroelectric crystal allowed to cool under no applied stress generally builds up a static charge of thousands of volts.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Such materials are used in motion sensors, where the tiny rise in temperature from a warm body entering the room is enough to produce a measurable voltage in the crystal.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] In turn, pyroelectricity is seen most strongly in materials that also display the ferroelectric effect, in which a stable electric dipole can be oriented or reversed by applying an electrostatic field.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Pyroelectricity is also a necessary consequence of ferroelectricity.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] This can be used to store information in ferroelectric capacitors, elements of ferroelectric RAM.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The most common such materials are lead zirconate titanate and barium titanate.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Aside from the uses mentioned above, their strong piezoelectric response is exploited in the design of high-frequency loudspeakers, transducers for sonar, and actuators for atomic force and scanning tunneling microscopes.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Temperature increases can cause grain boundaries to suddenly become insulating in some semiconducting ceramic materials, mostly mixtures of heavy metal titanates.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The critical transition temperature can be adjusted over a wide range by variations in chemistry.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] In such materials, current will pass through the material until joule heating brings it to the transition temperature, at which point the circuit will be broken and current flow will cease.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Such ceramics are used as self-controlled heating elements in, for example, the rear-window defrost circuits of automobiles.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] At the transition temperature, the material's dielectric response becomes theoretically infinite.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] While a lack of temperature control would rule out any practical use of the material near its critical temperature, the dielectric effect remains exceptionally strong even at much higher temperatures.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Titanates with critical temperatures far below room temperature have become synonymous with "ceramic" in the context of ceramic capacitors for just this reason.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Optically transparent materials focus on the response of a material to incoming light waves of a range of wavelengths.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Frequency selective optical filters can be utilized to alter or enhance the brightness and contrast of a digital image.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] This resonant mode of energy and data transmission via electromagnetic (light) wave propagation, though low powered, is virtually lossless.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Optical waveguides are used as components in Integrated optical circuits (e.g. light-emitting diodes, LEDs) or as the transmission medium in local and long haul optical communication systems.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Also of value to the emerging materials scientist is the sensitivity of materials to radiation in the thermal infrared (IR) portion of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] This heat-seeking ability is responsible for such diverse optical phenomena as night-vision and IR luminescence.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Thus, there is an increasing need in the military sector for high-strength, robust materials which have the capability to transmit light (electromagnetic waves) in the visible (0.4 – 0.7 micrometers) and mid-infrared (1 – 5 micrometers) regions of the spectrum.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] These materials are needed for applications requiring transparent armor, including next-generation high-speed missiles and pods, as well as protection against improvised explosive devices (IED).
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] In the 1960s, scientists at General Electric (GE) discovered that under the right manufacturing conditions, some ceramics, especially aluminium oxide (alumina), could be made translucent.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] These translucent materials were transparent enough to be used for containing the electrical plasma generated in high-pressure sodium street lamps.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] During the past two decades, additional types of transparent ceramics have been developed for applications such as nose cones for heat-seeking missiles, windows for fighter aircraft, and scintillation counters for computed tomography scanners.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Sialon (silicon aluminium oxynitride) has high strength, resistance to thermal shock, chemical and wear resistance, and low density.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] These ceramics are used in non-ferrous molten metal handling, weld pins, and the chemical industry.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Silicon carbide (SiC) is used as a susceptor in microwave furnaces, a commonly used abrasive, and as a refractory material.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Silicon nitride (Si3N4) is used as an abrasive powder.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Steatite (magnesium silicates) is used as an electrical insulator.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Titanium carbide is used in space shuttle re-entry shields and scratchproof watches.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Uranium oxide (UO2) is used as fuel in nuclear reactors.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Yttrium barium copper oxide (YBa2Cu3O7−x) is a high-temperature superconductor.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Zinc oxide (ZnO) is a semiconductor used in the construction of varistors.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Zirconium dioxide (zirconia), which in pure form undergoes many phase changes between room temperature and practical sintering temperatures, can be chemically "stabilized" in several different forms.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Its high oxygen ion conductivity recommends it for use in fuel cells and automotive oxygen sensors.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] In another variant, metastable structures can impart transformation toughening for mechanical applications; most ceramic knife blades are made of this material.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Partially stabilised zirconia (PSZ) is much less brittle than other ceramics and is used for metal forming tools, valves and liners, abrasive slurries, kitchen knives and bearings subject to severe abrasion.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Technical, also known as engineering, advanced, special, and fine ceramics.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Frequently, the raw materials of modern ceramics do not include clays.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Composite materials**:** particulate reinforced, fiber reinforced, combinations of oxides and non-oxides.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Each one of these classes can be developed into unique material properties.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Carbon–ceramic brake disks for vehicles: highly resistant to brake fade at high temperatures.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Advanced composite ceramic and metal matrices have been designed for most modern armoured fighting vehicles because they offer superior penetrating resistance against shaped charge (HEAT rounds) and kinetic energy penetrators.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramics such as alumina and boron carbide have been used as plates in ballistic armored vests to repel high-velocity rifle fire.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Such plates are known commonly as small arms protective inserts, or SAPIs.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Similar low-weight material is used to protect the cockpits of some military aircraft.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramic ball bearings can be used in place of steel.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Their greater hardness results in lower susceptibility to wear.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramic bearings typically last triple the lifetime of steel bearings.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] They deform less than steel under load, resulting in less contact with the bearing retainer walls and lower friction.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] In very high-speed applications, heat from friction causes more problems for metal bearings than ceramic bearings.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramics are chemically resistant to corrosion and are preferred for environments where steel bearings would rust.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] In some applications their electricity-insulating properties are advantageous.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Drawbacks to ceramic bearings include significantly higher cost, susceptibility to damage under shock loads, and the potential to wear steel parts due to ceramics' greater hardness.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] In the early 1980s Toyota researched production of an adiabatic engine using ceramic components in the hot gas area.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The use of ceramics would have allowed temperatures exceeding 1650 °C.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Advantages would include lighter materials and a smaller cooling system (or no cooling system at all), leading to major weight reduction.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The expected increase of fuel efficiency (due to higher operating temperatures, demonstrated in Carnot's theorem) could not be verified experimentally.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] It was found that heat transfer on the hot ceramic cylinder wall was greater than the heat transfer to a cooler metal wall.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] This is because the cooler gas film on a metal surface acts as a thermal insulator.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Thus, despite the desirable properties of ceramics, prohibitive production costs and limited advantages have prevented widespread ceramic engine component adoption.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] In addition, small imperfections in ceramic material along with low fracture toughness can lead to cracking and potentially dangerous equipment failure.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Such engines are possible experimentally, but mass production is not feasible with current technology.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Experiments with ceramic parts for gas turbine engines are being conducted.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Currently, even blades made of advanced metal alloys used in the engines' hot section require cooling and careful monitoring of operating temperatures.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Turbine engines made with ceramics could operate more efficiently, providing for greater range and payload.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Recent advances have been made in ceramics which include bioceramics such as dental implants and synthetic bones.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Hydroxyapatite, the major mineral component of bone, has been made synthetically from several biological and chemical components and can be formed into ceramic materials.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Orthopedic implants coated with these materials bond readily to bone and other tissues in the body without rejection or inflammatory reaction.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] They are of great interest for gene delivery and tissue engineering scaffolding.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Most hydroxyapatite ceramics are quite porous and lack mechanical strength and are therefore used solely to coat metal orthopedic devices to aid in forming a bond to bone or as bone fillers.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] They are also used as fillers for orthopedic plastic screws to aid in reducing inflammation and increase the absorption of these plastic materials.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Work is being done to make strong, fully dense nanocrystalline hydroxyapatite ceramic materials for orthopedic weight bearing devices, replacing foreign metal and plastic orthopedic materials with a synthetic but naturally occurring bone mineral.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ultimately, these ceramic materials may be used as bone replacement, or with the incorporation of protein collagens, the manufacture of synthetic bones.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Applications for actinide-containing ceramic materials include nuclear fuels for burning excess plutonium (Pu), or a chemically inert source of alpha radiation in power supplies for uncrewed space vehicles or microelectronic devices.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Use and disposal of radioactive actinides require immobilization in a durable host material.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Long half-life radionuclides such as actinide are immobilized using chemically durable crystalline materials based on polycrystalline ceramics and large single crystals.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] High-tech ceramics are used for producing watch cases.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] The material is valued by watchmakers for its light weight, scratch resistance, durability, and smooth touch.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] IWC is one of the brands that pioneered the use of ceramic in watchmaking.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramics are used in the design of mobile phone bodies due to their high hardness, resistance to scratches, and ability to dissipate heat.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramic's thermal management properties help in maintaining optimal device temperatures during heavy use enhancing performance.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Additionally, ceramic materials can support wireless charging and offer better signal transmission compared to metals, which can interfere with antennas.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Companies like Apple and Samsung have incorporated ceramic in their devices.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Ceramics made of silicon carbide are used in pump and valve components because of their corrosion resistance characteristics.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] It is also used in nuclear reactors as fuel cladding materials due to their ability to withstand radiation and thermal stress.
[src:buckingham-potential/ceramic] Other uses of Silicon carbide ceramics include paper manufacturing, ballistics, chemical production, and as pipe system components.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The law states that the magnitude, or absolute value, of the attractive or repulsive electrostatic force between two point charges is directly proportional to the product of the magnitudes of their charges and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between them.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Here, *k*e is the **Coulomb constant**, *q*1 and *q*2 are the quantities of each charge, and the scalar *r* is the distance between the charges.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The force is along the straight line joining the two bodies.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] If the charges have the same sign, the electrostatic force between them makes them repel; if they have different signs, the force between them makes them attract.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Being an inverse-square law, the law is similar to Isaac Newton's inverse-square law of universal gravitation, but gravitational forces always make things attract, while electrostatic forces make charges attract or repel.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Also, gravitational forces are much weaker than electrostatic forces.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Coulomb's law can be used to derive Gauss's law, and vice versa.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] In the case of a single point charge at rest, the two laws are equivalent, expressing the same physical law in different ways.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The law has been tested extensively, and observations have upheld the law on the scale from 10−16 m to 108 m.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The time-dependent generalization of Coulomb's law is given by Jefimenko's equations, which describe the electric field and magnetic fields generated by time-dependent distributions of electric charge and current.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Ancient cultures around the Mediterranean knew that certain objects, such as rods of amber, could be rubbed with cat's fur to attract light objects like feathers and pieces of paper.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Thales of Miletus made the first recorded description of static electricity around 600 BC, when he noticed that friction could make a piece of amber attract small objects.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] In 1600, English scientist William Gilbert made a careful study of electricity and magnetism, distinguishing the lodestone effect from static electricity produced by rubbing amber.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] He coined the Neo-Latin word *electricus* ("of amber" or "like amber", from ἤλεκτρον [*elektron*], the Greek word for "amber") to refer to the property of attracting small objects after being rubbed.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] This association gave rise to the English words "electric" and "electricity", which made their first appearance in print in Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica* of 1646.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Based on experiments with electrically charged spheres, Joseph Priestley of England was among the first to propose that electrical force followed an inverse-square law, similar to Newton's law of universal gravitation.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] However, he did not generalize or elaborate on this.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] In 1767, he conjectured that the force between charges varied as the inverse square of the distance.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] In 1769, Scottish physicist John Robison announced that, according to his measurements, the force of repulsion between two spheres with charges of the same sign varied as *x*−2.06.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] In the early 1770s, the dependence of the force between charged bodies upon both distance and charge had already been discovered, but not published, by Henry Cavendish of England.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Finally, in 1785, the French physicist Charles-Augustin de Coulomb published his first three reports of electricity and magnetism where he stated his law.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] This publication was essential to the development of the theory of electromagnetism.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] He used a torsion balance to study the repulsion and attraction forces of charged particles, and determined that the magnitude of the electric force between two point charges is directly proportional to the product of the charges and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between them.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The torsion balance consists of a bar suspended from its middle by a thin fiber.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The fiber acts as a very weak torsion spring.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] In Coulomb's experiment, the torsion balance was an insulating rod with a metal-coated ball attached to one end, suspended by a silk thread.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The ball was charged with a known charge of static electricity, and a second charged ball of the same polarity was brought near it.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The two charged balls repelled one another, twisting the fiber through a certain angle, which could be read from a scale on the instrument.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] By knowing how much force it took to twist the fiber through a given angle, Coulomb was able to calculate the force between the balls and derive his inverse-square proportionality law.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] where ${\textstyle \mathbf {r_{12}=r_{1}-r_{2}} }$ is the displacement vector between the charges, ${\textstyle {\hat {\mathbf {r} }}_{12}}$ a unit vector pointing from ${\textstyle q_{2}}$ to ${\textstyle q_{1}}$ , and $\varepsilon _{0}$ the electric constant.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Here, ${\textstyle \mathbf {\hat {r}} _{12}}$ is used for the vector notation.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The electrostatic force ${\textstyle \mathbf {F} _{2}}$ experienced by $q_{2}$ , according to Newton's third law, is ${\textstyle \mathbf {F} _{2}=-\mathbf {F} _{1}}$ .
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] If both charges have the same sign (like charges) then the product $q_{1}q_{2}$ is positive and the direction of the force on $q_{1}$ is given by ${\textstyle {\widehat {\mathbf {r} }}_{12}}$ ; the charges repel each other.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] If the charges have opposite signs then the product $q_{1}q_{2}$ is negative and the direction of the force on $q_{1}$ is ${\textstyle -{\hat {\mathbf {r} }}_{12}}$ ; the charges attract each other.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The law of superposition allows Coulomb's law to be extended to include any number of point charges.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The force acting on a point charge due to a system of point charges is simply the vector addition of the individual forces acting alone on that point charge due to each one of the charges.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The resulting force vector is parallel to the electric field vector at that point, with that point charge removed.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] where $q_{i}$ is the magnitude of the *i* th charge, ${\textstyle \mathbf {r} _{i}}$ is the vector from its position to $\mathbf {r}$ and ${\textstyle {\hat {\mathbf {r} }}_{i}}$ is the unit vector in the direction of $\mathbf {r} _{i}$ .
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] In this case, the principle of linear superposition is also used.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] For a continuous charge distribution, an integral over the region containing the charge is equivalent to an infinite summation, treating each infinitesimal element of space as a point charge $dq$ .
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The distribution of charge is usually linear, surface or volumetric.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Charge is always discrete in reality, and the "continuous charge" assumption is just an approximation that is not supposed to allow $|\mathbf {r} -\mathbf {r'} |=0$ to be analyzed.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The constant $\varepsilon _{0}$ is the vacuum electric permittivity.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The charges must not overlap (e.g. they must be distinct point charges).
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The charges must be stationary with respect to a non-accelerating frame of reference.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The last of these is known as the electrostatic approximation.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] When movement takes place, an extra factor is introduced, which alters the force produced on the two objects.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] This extra part of the force is called the magnetic force.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] For slow movement, the magnetic force is minimal and Coulomb's law can still be considered approximately correct.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] A more accurate approximation in this case is, however, the Weber force.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] When the charges are moving more quickly in relation to each other or accelerations occur, Maxwell's equations and Einstein's theory of relativity must be taken into consideration.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] An electric field is a vector field that associates to each point in space the Coulomb force experienced by a unit test charge.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The strength and direction of the Coulomb force ${\textstyle \mathbf {F} }$ on a charge ${\textstyle q_{t}}$ depends on the electric field ${\textstyle \mathbf {E} }$ established by other charges that it finds itself in, such that ${\textstyle \mathbf {F} =q_{t}\mathbf {E} }$ .
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] In the simplest case, the field is considered to be generated solely by a single source point charge.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] More generally, the field can be generated by a distribution of charges who contribute to the overall by the principle of superposition.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] If the field is generated by a positive source point charge ${\textstyle q}$ , the direction of the electric field points along lines directed radially outwards from it, i.e. in the direction that a positive point test charge ${\textstyle q_{t}}$ would move if placed in the field.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] For a negative point source charge, the direction is radially inwards.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The magnitude of the electric field **E** can be derived from Coulomb's law.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Coulomb's law holds even within atoms, correctly describing the force between the positively charged atomic nucleus and each of the negatively charged electrons.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] This simple law also correctly accounts for the forces that bind atoms together to form molecules and for the forces that bind atoms and molecules together to form solids and liquids.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Generally, as the distance between ions increases, the force of attraction, and binding energy, approach zero and ionic bonding is less favorable.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] As the magnitude of opposing charges increases, energy increases and ionic bonding is more favorable.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Strictly speaking, Gauss's law cannot be derived from Coulomb's law alone, since Coulomb's law gives the electric field due to an individual, electrostatic point charge only.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] However, Gauss's law *can* be proven from Coulomb's law if it is assumed, in addition, that the electric field obeys the superposition principle.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The superposition principle states that the resulting field is the vector sum of fields generated by each particle (or the integral, if the charges are distributed smoothly in space).
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Using the "sifting property" of the Dirac delta function, we arrive at $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {E} (\mathbf {r} )={\frac {\rho (\mathbf {r} )}{\varepsilon _{0}}},$ which is the differential form of Gauss's law, as desired.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Since Coulomb's law only applies to stationary charges, there is no reason to expect Gauss's law to hold for moving charges based on this derivation alone.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] In fact, Gauss's law does hold for moving charges, and, in this respect, Gauss's law is more general than Coulomb's law.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] It is true for all $\mathbf {r} \neq \mathbf {r'}$ that $\nabla _{\mathbf {r} }\cdot \mathbf {e} (\mathbf {r,r'} )=0$ .
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Consider now a compact set $V\subseteq R^{3}$ having a piecewise smooth boundary $\partial V$ such that $\Omega \cap V=\emptyset$ .
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Therefore the flux through a closed surface generated by some charge density outside (the surface) is null.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Now consider $\mathbf {r} _{0}\in \Omega$ , and $B_{R}(\mathbf {r} _{0})\subseteq \Omega$ as the sphere centered in $\mathbf {r} _{0}$ having R as radius (it exists because $\Omega$ is an open set).
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Let $\mathbf {E} _{B_{R}}$ and $\mathbf {E} _{C}$ be the electric field created inside and outside the sphere respectively.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The last equality follows by observing that $(\Omega \setminus B_{R}(\mathbf {r} _{0}))\cap B_{R}(\mathbf {r} _{0})=\emptyset$ , and the argument above.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Where the last equality follows by the mean value theorem for integrals.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Strictly speaking, Coulomb's law cannot be derived from Gauss's law alone, since Gauss's law does not give any information regarding the curl of **E** (see Helmholtz decomposition and Faraday's law).
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] However, Coulomb's law *can* be proven from Gauss's law if it is assumed, in addition, that the electric field from a point charge is spherically symmetric (this assumption, like Coulomb's law itself, is exactly true if the charge is stationary, and approximately true if the charge is in motion).
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] By the assumption of spherical symmetry, the integrand is a constant which can be taken out of the integral.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The result is $4\pi r^{2}{\hat {\mathbf {r} }}\cdot \mathbf {E} (\mathbf {r} )={\frac {Q}{\varepsilon _{0}}}$ where **r̂** is a unit vector pointing radially away from the charge.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Again by spherical symmetry, **E** points in the radial direction, and so we get $\mathbf {E} (\mathbf {r} )={\frac {Q}{4\pi \varepsilon _{0}}}{\frac {\hat {\mathbf {r} }}{r^{2}}}$ which is essentially equivalent to Coulomb's law.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Thus the inverse-square law dependence of the electric field in Coulomb's law follows from Gauss's law.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Coulomb's law can be used to gain insight into the form of the magnetic field generated by moving charges since by special relativity, in certain cases the magnetic field can be shown to be a transformation of forces caused by the electric field.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] When no acceleration is involved in a particle's history, Coulomb's law can be assumed on any test particle in its own inertial frame, supported by symmetry arguments in solving Maxwell's equation, shown above.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Coulomb's law can be expanded to moving test particles to be of the same form.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] This assumption is supported by Lorentz force law which, unlike Coulomb's law is not limited to stationary test charges.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] This form of solutions need not obey Newton's third law as is the case in the framework of special relativity (yet without violating relativistic-energy momentum conservation).
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Note that the expression for electric field reduces to Coulomb's law for non-relativistic speeds of the point charge and that the magnetic field in non-relativistic limit (approximating $\beta \ll 1$ ) can be applied to electric currents to get the Biot–Savart law.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] These solutions, when expressed in retarded time also correspond to the general solution of Maxwell's equations given by solutions of Liénard–Wiechert potential, due to the validity of Coulomb's law within its specific range of application.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Also note that the spherical symmetry for gauss law on stationary charges is not valid for moving charges owing to the breaking of symmetry by the specification of direction of velocity in the problem.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Agreement with Maxwell's equations can also be manually verified for the above two equations.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The **Coulomb potential** admits continuum states (with *E* > 0), describing electron-proton scattering, as well as discrete bound states, representing the hydrogen atom.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] However, the equivalent results of the classical Born derivations for the Coulomb problem are thought to be strictly accidental.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The Coulomb potential, and its derivation, can be seen as a special case of the Yukawa potential, which is the case where the exchanged boson – the photon – has no rest mass.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] It is possible to verify Coulomb's law with a simple experiment.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Consider two small spheres of mass m and same-sign charge q , hanging from two ropes of negligible mass of length l .
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] The forces acting on each sphere are three: the weight $mg$ , the rope tension $\mathbf {T}$ and the electric force $\mathbf {F}$ .
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] If we now discharge one of the spheres, and we put it in contact with the charged sphere, each one of them acquires a charge ${\textstyle {\frac {q}{2}}}$ .
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] Measuring the angles $\theta _{1}$ and $\theta _{2}$ and the distance between the charges $\mathbf {L} _{1}$ and $\mathbf {L} _{2}$ is sufficient to verify that the equality is true taking into account the experimental error.
[src:buckingham-potential/coulomb-s-law] In this way, the verification is limited to measuring the distance between the charges and checking that the division approximates the theoretical value.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] In chemistry and atomic physics, an **electron shell** may be thought of as an orbit that electrons follow around an atom's nucleus.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] The closest shell to the nucleus is called the "1 shell" (also called the "K shell"), followed by the "2 shell" (or "L shell"), then the "3 shell" (or "M shell"), and so on further and further from the nucleus.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] The shells correspond to the principal quantum numbers (*n* = 1, 2, 3, 4 ...) or are labeled alphabetically with the letters used in X-ray notation (K, L, M, ...).
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Each period on the conventional periodic table of elements represents an electron shell.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Each shell can contain only a fixed number of electrons: the first shell can hold up to two electrons, the second shell can hold up to eight electrons, the third shell can hold up to 18, continuing as the general formula of the *n*th shell being able to hold up to 2(*n*2) electrons.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] For an explanation of why electrons exist in these shells, see electron configuration.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Each shell consists of one or more *subshells*, and each subshell consists of one or more atomic orbitals.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] In 1913, Niels Bohr proposed a model of the atom, giving the arrangement of electrons in their sequential orbits.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] At that time, Bohr allowed the capacity of the inner orbit of the atom to increase to eight electrons as the atoms got larger, and "in the scheme given below the number of electrons in this [outer] ring is arbitrary put equal to the normal valency of the corresponding element".
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Using these and other constraints, he proposed configurations that are in accord with those now known only for the first six elements.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] The shell terminology comes from Arnold Sommerfeld's modification of the 1913 Bohr model.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] During this period Bohr was working with Walther Kossel, whose papers in 1914 and in 1916 called the orbits "shells".
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Sommerfeld retained Bohr's planetary model, but added mildly elliptical orbits (characterized by additional quantum numbers *ℓ* and *m*) to explain the fine spectroscopic structure of some elements.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] The multiple electrons with the same principal quantum number (*n*) had close orbits that formed a "shell" of positive thickness instead of the circular orbit of Bohr's model which orbits called "rings" were described by a plane.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] The existence of electron shells was first observed experimentally in Charles Barkla's and Henry Moseley's X-ray absorption studies.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Moseley's work did not directly concern the study of electron shells, because he was trying to prove that the periodic table was not arranged by weight, but by the charge of the protons in the nucleus.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] However, because the number of electrons in an electrically neutral atom equals the number of protons, this work was extremely important to Niels Bohr who mentioned Moseley's work several times in his 1962 interview.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Moseley was part of Rutherford's group, as was Niels Bohr.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Moseley measured the frequencies of X-rays emitted by every element between calcium and zinc and found that the frequencies became greater as the elements got heavier.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] This led to the theory that electrons were emitting X-rays when they were shifted to lower shells.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] This led to the conclusion that the electrons were in Kossel's shells with a definite limit per shell, labeling them with the letters K, L, M, N, O, P, and Q.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] The origin of this terminology was alphabetic.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Barkla, who worked independently from Moseley as an X-ray spectrometry experimentalist, first noticed two distinct types of scattering from shooting X-rays at elements in 1909 and named them "A" and "B".
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Barkla described these two types of X-ray diffraction: the first was unconnected with the type of material used in the experiment and could be polarized.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] The second diffraction beam he called "fluorescent" because it depended on the irradiated material.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] It was not known what these lines meant at the time, but in 1911 Barkla decided there might be scattering lines previous to "A", so he began at "K".
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] However, later experiments indicated that the K absorption lines are produced by the innermost electrons.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] These letters were later found to correspond to the *n* values 1, 2, 3, etc. that were used in the Bohr model.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] They are used in the spectroscopic Siegbahn notation.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] The work of assigning electrons to shells was continued from 1913 to 1925 by many chemists and a few physicists.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Einstein and Rutherford, who did not follow chemistry, were unaware of the chemists who were developing electron shell theories of the periodic table from a chemistry point of view, such as Irving Langmuir, Charles Bury, J.J.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] So when Bohr outlined his electron shell atomic theory in 1922, there was no mathematical formula for the theory.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] So Rutherford said he was hard put "to form an idea of how you arrive at your conclusions".
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Einstein said of Bohr's 1922 paper that his "electron-shells of the atoms together with their significance for chemistry appeared to me like a miracle – and appears to me as a miracle even today".
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Arnold Sommerfeld, who had followed the *Atombau* structure of electrons instead of Bohr who was familiar with the chemists' views of electron structure, spoke of Bohr's 1921 lecture and 1922 article on the shell model as "the greatest advance in atomic structure since 1913".
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] However, the electron shell development of Niels Bohr was basically the same theory as that of the chemist Charles Rugeley Bury in his 1921 paper.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] When the modern quantum mechanics theory was put forward based on Heisenberg's matrix mechanics and Schrödinger's wave equation, these quantum numbers were kept in the current quantum theory but were changed to *n* being the principal quantum number, and *m* being the magnetic quantum number.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] However, the final form of the electron shell model still in use today for the number of electrons in shells was discovered in 1923 by Edmund Stoner, who introduced the principle that the *n*th shell was described by 2(*n*2).
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Seeing this in 1925, Wolfgang Pauli added a fourth quantum number, "spin", during the old quantum theory period of the Sommerfeld-Bohr Solar System atom to complete the modern electron shell theory.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Each shell is composed of one or more subshells, which are themselves composed of atomic orbitals.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Therefore, the K shell, which contains only an s subshell, can hold up to 2 electrons; the L shell, which contains an s and a p, can hold up to 2 + 6 = 8 electrons, and so forth; in general, the *n*th shell can hold up to 2*n*2 electrons.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Although that formula gives the maximum in principle, that maximum is only *achieved* (in known elements) for the first four shells (K, L, M, N).
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] No known element has more than 32 electrons in any one shell.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] This is because the subshells are filled according to the Aufbau principle.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] The first elements to have more than 32 electrons in one shell would belong to the g-block of period 8 of the periodic table.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] These elements would have some electrons in their 5g subshell and thus have more than 32 electrons in the O shell (fifth principal shell).
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Although it is sometimes stated that all the electrons in a shell have the same energy, this is an approximation.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] However, the electrons in one *subshell* do have exactly the same level of energy, with later subshells having more energy per electron than earlier ones.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] This effect is great enough that the energy ranges associated with shells can overlap.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] The filling of the shells and subshells with electrons proceeds from subshells of lower energy to subshells of higher energy.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] This follows the *n + ℓ rule* which is also commonly known as the Madelung rule.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Subshells with a lower *n + ℓ* value are filled before those with higher *n + ℓ* values.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] In the case of equal *n + ℓ* values, the subshell with a lower *n* value is filled first.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Because of this, the later shells are filled over vast sections of the periodic table.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] The K shell fills in the first period (hydrogen and helium), while the L shell fills in the second (lithium to neon).
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] However, the M shell starts filling at sodium (element 11) but does not finish filling till copper (element 29), and the N shell is even slower: it starts filling at potassium (element 19) but does not finish filling till ytterbium (element 70).
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] The O, P, and Q shells begin filling in the known elements (respectively at rubidium, caesium, and francium), but they are not complete even at the heaviest known element, oganesson (element 118).
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] The list below gives the elements arranged by increasing atomic number and shows the number of electrons per shell.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] At a glance, the subsets of the list show obvious patterns.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] In particular, every set of five elements ( electric blue) before each noble gas (group 18, yellow) heavier than helium have successive numbers of electrons in the outermost shell, namely three to seven.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] Sorting the table by chemical group shows additional patterns, especially with respect to the last two outermost shells.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] The list below is primarily consistent with the Aufbau principle.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] However, there are a number of exceptions to the rule; for example palladium (atomic number 46) has no electrons in the fifth shell, unlike other atoms with *lower* atomic number.
[src:buckingham-potential/electron-shell] The elements past 108 have such short half-lives that their electron configurations have not yet been measured, and so predictions have been inserted instead.
